events.title: Putting Google Cloud Together: Querying App Engine logs with BigQuery
prerequisites: Proficient in Python
Latest version of App Engine SDK for Python

Can run dev_appserver.py locally
Have created a new App Engine application hosted on appspot.com
Can deploy app on appspot.com using appcfg.py

Python 2.7 installed
Working Gmail email address
Have completed the getting started for App Engine / Python27 guide
events.abstract:
This session will show you how to use multiple Google Technologies together in order to automate import and query your App Engine logs from Big Query including:
- Using the Map Reduce API and the new Log API to read your App Engine logs
- Store your logs into Google Storage using robot account
- Import your logs into Big Query and query them from the web interface or programmatically.

events.title: Android Dev Tools Bootcamp
prerequisites: - Proficiency in Java
Please ensure you have the following installed, can create a new Android project, and run it in the Emulator:
- Android SDK with 4.0.3 system image installed from SDK Manager
- Eclipse Classic with ADT Plugin
events.abstract: We’ll get our hands dirty with all the latest goodness in the Android Developer toolset.  You should leave this session equipped with a broad understanding of how the pieces fit together and how to get maximum benefit from them.

events.title: Advanced HTML Page Authoring Using Modern CSS Features
prerequisites:
A text editor installed and ready to use
Chrome version 21 - download canary version
Working knowledge of CSS 2.1
Familiarity with HTML page layout
events.abstract: In this code lab, we'll explore new CSS3 features and show you how to use them, to build amazing HTML pages and web applications. For example, we'll cover CSS3 flexbox, CSS3 multi column and many other features. We'll also review CSS features that make web pages more compelling e.g via using filters.

events.title: Building Google+ Hangout Apps
prerequisites: - Experience with basic web concepts
- Proficiency in JavaScript, CSS, and HTML
- A place to host one or more files in a public place on the internet
- A code editor of your choice that will edit JavaScript
- A semi-transparent image that will make a good attachment to your face (a hat, glasses, etc)
- Download the Simple Hangout App and host it on your public web server
- If you need a hosting solution, you can use our App Engine sample project
events.abstract: Google+ Hangouts bring you face-to-face with 9 other people from across the world with video.  Google+ Hangout Apps are shared activities---your content inside a Hangout!  In this lab, using Javascript and a web server, you will learn how to use the APIs to build a shared application that stays synced across all participants, uses delightful media effects, and authenticates using Google+.  We will discuss best practices, debugging, app design, animation, the latest API releases, and more.

events.title: Implementing Your First End-to-End Drive App
prerequisites: Working knowledge of Java.
Download and install Eclipse, the Google Plugin for Eclipse, and the App Engine SDK for Java
events.abstract: Google engineers will be on-hand to help you get Google Drive integration working with your own application.  We will walk through a brief introductory sample application, with a goal of getting everyone's Drive integration up and running before the end of the session.

events.title: Android App Monetization
prerequisites: Please ensure you have the following installed, can create a new Android project, and run it in the Emulator:
- Android SDK with 4.0.3 system image installed from SDK Manager
- Eclipse Classic with ADT Plugin OR IntelliJ IDEA Community Edition
- Google AdMob Ads SDK (Rev 6 from SDK Manager)
- Google Play Billing Library (Rev 2 from SDK Manager)
- (Optional, needed for testing) Google Play Android Developer Console Account
- (Optional) AdMob publisher account
events.abstract: Go hands-on with all the different monetization technologies available to an Android app developer.  Build an app (or equip one you already have) with AdMob ads and in-app payments, in a way that’s rewarding to you, pleasant for your users, and highly secure for everyone.

events.title: Master the Latest YouTube Data API
prerequisites:
Familiarity with HTML5, JavaScript, and the jQuery library.
Access to a webserver (OS X's built in web sharing works, or App Engine's development server, etc.)
An extra credit exercise will require some experience with Python, App Engine, and SQLite (comes preinstalled on OS X and some Linux distros.
events.abstract: The YouTube Data API is changing, and we're ready to give a first look. We'll go into more details about the backend infrastructure powering the new API, as well as the new, modern libraries that will power the next generation of client code.

events.title: Android Support Library and Action Bar
prerequisites:
- Proficiency in Java

Intermediate knowledge of Android
Please ensure you have the following installed, can create a new Android project, and run it in the Emulator:
- Android SDK with 4.0.3 system image installed from SDK Manager
- Eclipse Classic with ADT Plugin
events.abstract: Build an app that uses the support library to provide a smooth, consistent user experience on devices ranging from tablets running the latest release back to simple handsets running Froyo

events.title: Integrate Web Intents into Your Web Application Today
prerequisites: Proficiency in JavaScript
Chrome 21+ installed - see canary channel
Create a profile you don't mind adding dev extensions to
Build the Hello World example of a Chrome app
Look at webintents.org
(Optional) Prepare to publish apps to the Chrome Web Store
events.abstract: Web Intents is the future of inter-application communication. In this Code Lab the creators of Web Intents will give you one on one advice about how to integrate Web Intents into your application.

events.title: Not Just a Map
prerequisites: Proficiency in JavaScript
events.abstract: Using a real-estate site as a case study, we'll walk you through creating a website from scratch that takes full advantage of powerful Maps API's that got far beyond markers and infowindows.  We'll show you how features like the distance matrix, autogenerating tours, custom streetview, and more can enhance the user experience of your map related site.

events.title: Bullseye : Your First Dart App
prerequisites: Proficiency in HTML, CSS, and either JavaScript or Java.
Object oriented programming.
Familiarity with browser programming and the Dev Tools is a plus.
Download the Dart Editor before the session
Review Dart articles
events.abstract: Build your first Dart app! We'll lead you through the process of building a modern web app with the Dart platform, using both client-side and server-side Dart. You will explore the language, libraries, editor, and integration with Chromium. You'll leave this session with a working Dart app that works in modern browsers.

events.title: Building Web applications in JavaScript that use Google APIs
prerequisites: Proficiency in JavaScript
events.abstract: In this code lab, we will build a photo slideshow application powered by real time Google+ activity feeds using the Google API JavaScript client library. You will learn to display photos posted by particular users or related to specific topics or hash tags purely in HTML and JavaScript without the necessity of setting up and running a dynamic server.  The code lab will also explore other Google APIs such as Calendar and Books.

events.title: Google+ History
prerequisites: Proficiency in JavaScript, HTML, and CSS.
events.abstract: Google+ history makes it easy for your site or app’s users to privately save and optionally share their online activity... and the early developer preview is ready for you!  Join this session to build a basic implementation using the documentation and a starter project.

events.title: Build Maps with Google Maps Engine
prerequisites: Proficiency in JavaScript
events.abstract: Google Maps Engine allows organizations to process and publish their unique and compelling geospatial data entirely on Google's infrastructure. We'll show you how to use Maps Engine and how users are already using it to build custom maps. Then we will teach you how to build applications that can leverage private Maps Engine Maps as well as the ever increasing amount of value-added public maps via the new Maps Gallery

events.title: Building REST APIs for Mobile with App Engine
prerequisites: Familiarity with Google App Engine and the Java runtime
Eclipse
The most recent version of the Google Plugin for Eclipse
The most recent version of the Google App Engine SDK
The Android SDK
The ADT Plugin for Eclipse
Android 2.2 (API 8) installed via the Android SDK Manager
events.abstract: This code lab will walk you through the process of building two APIs for a mobile game. You’ll learn how to build the backend using Google App Engine, as well as how to consume the APIs in Android applications.

events.title: Building Android Applications that use Web APIs
prerequisites: - Proficiency in Java
Please ensure you have the following installed, can create a new Android project, and run it in the Emulator:
- Android SDK with 4.0.3 system image installed from SDK Manager
- Eclipse Classic with ADT Plugin
It is also recommended that you become familiar with Google APIs by viewing the webinar at Google I/O 101: Google APIs: Getting Started Quickly.
events.abstract: In this session, we will demonstrate how to enrich your Android application by integrating it with Google APIs using the Google API client for Java.  You will learn how to use the features of the Java client efficiently and securely, how to implement authentication for API calls, and how to perform Android-specific optimizations.

events.title: Monetizing your Web Apps: A Walkthrough of Google Wallet APIs for Mobile and Desktop
prerequisites:
Proficiency in JavaScript
Proficiency in App Engine (either the Python or Java runtime)
events.abstract: Accepting payments on the web can be tricky and Google Wallet aims to simplify this process.  During this codelab, we'll walk through building a basic desktop and mobile web site to sell goods and track user purchases.  By attending this codelab, you can expect to learn more about Google Wallet APIs, developer tools, and best practices for payment processing.
